In Figure \ref{balmer}, we compare our extinction corrections from the monochromatic 24~\micron\ luminosity to extinction-corrected {\hbox{H$\alpha$}}\ luminosities from the Balmer decrement, measured from the ratio of the {\hbox{H$\alpha$}}\ and {\hbox{H$\beta$}}\ emission lines.  Most of our primary calibration sample consists of dusty star-forming galaxies (i.e.\ LIRGs) that heavily attenuate the {\hbox{H$\beta$}}\ emission line and to a lesser extent the {\hbox{H$\alpha$}}\ emission line.  We indicate galaxies with A$_{{\hbox{H$\alpha$}}} > 1$~mag that, in essence, results in an attenuation factor of ${\mathrel{\hbox{\rlap{\lower.55ex \hbox{$\sim$}} \kern-.3em \raise.4ex \hbox{$>$}}}}$2.5 for {\hbox{H$\alpha$}}\ and a factor ${\mathrel{\hbox{\rlap{\lower.55ex \hbox{$\sim$}} \kern-.3em \raise.4ex \hbox{$>$}}}}$3.6 for {\hbox{H$\beta$}}.  For many sources the results are consistent.  But, there is a sample of highly attenuated objects, A$_{{\hbox{H$\alpha$}}} > 1$~mag, where we see big deviations (at the higher extinction-corrected {\hbox{H$\alpha$}}\ luminosities the Balmer decrement corrections saturate).  The likely explanation for this attenuation is that the interstellar medium (ISM) at {\hbox{H$\beta$}}\ is optically thick, so we are only seeing the ``skin" of the star-forming region (down to where $\tau \sim 1$ for {\hbox{H$\beta$}}), whereas we can see deeper into the star-forming region for {\hbox{H$\alpha$}}.  Balmer absorption could be another issue.  Figure \ref{balmer} suggests it is a significant contributor, since there are many galaxies where correcting with the Balmer decrement overcorrects {\hbox{H$\alpha$}}.  Only about half the sources in the primary calibration sample for A$_{{\hbox{H$\alpha$}}} > 1$~mag allow us to extinction correct using the Balmer decrement and $\sim 10 \%$ of the sample have unreliable corrections due to {\hbox{H$\beta$}}\ being heavily attenuated.  For this reason, we adopt the {\hbox{L$_{\mathrm{H} \alpha}$ + 0.020$\times$L$_{\mathrm{24~\micron}}$}}\ method as the best estimator for the total {\hbox{H$\alpha$}}\ emission for our primary calibration sample.

